questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: This region is known as the 'zone of inhibitors'.
questions.explanation: False. This area is correctly termed the 'zone of inhibition,' which is the area around an antimicrobial disk where bacterial growth has been prevented.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: This is known as a petri dish (or agar plate).
questions.explanation: True. The image shows a petri dish filled with a solid growth medium called agar, which is used for culturing microorganisms.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: These are 8 mm filter papers.
questions.explanation: False. The standard size for filter paper disks used in antibiotic susceptibility testing (Kirby-Bauer method) is 6 mm in diameter.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: It is not important to spread the bacteria evenly here.
questions.explanation: False. It is critical to create a uniform lawn of bacteria to ensure that the zone of inhibition is measured accurately and the results are reliable.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Tweezers must be sterilized in 70% ethanol.
questions.explanation: True. To prevent contamination of the agar plate and the antibiotic disks, instruments like tweezers (forceps) must be sterilized using aseptic techniques, such as dipping in 70% ethanol and flaming.
